Date: 25 June 2026
Platform: LabEx Corporation – Project Phoenix
Duration: ~45 minutes
Objective: Learn and practice Linux user and group management commands
Key Commands Practiced:

whoami, uname -a, uptime
useradd, passwd, usermod, userdel
groupadd, usermod -aG
File redirection (>, >>)

What I Did (Step-by-Step Summary):

Created system report using whoami, uname -a, and uptime
Created multiple user accounts with different options (home directory, custom shell, etc.)
Set and changed passwords
Modified user properties and added users to groups
Deleted users (with and without home directories)
Inspected /etc/passwd and /etc/group files

Key Learnings:

Linux uses /etc/passwd and /etc/shadow for user information
Importance of proper permissions when managing user home directories
Difference between useradd and adduser
How to safely delete user accounts without leaving orphan files
Real-world importance of following security policies when managing users

Real-World Application:
In a company these skills are used daily for:

Onboarding new employees (creating accounts)
Managing access rights (adding to groups)
Offboarding staff (disabling/deleting accounts)
Troubleshooting “user cannot login” issues

Challenges Faced & How I Solved Them:

Typo in filename (systemreporty.txt) → Fixed by using consistent naming (system_report.txt)
Learned to use >> for appending instead of overwriting
